ownedComment.body: Author:BohlenMa. Created:15.12.03 16:37. Title:. Comment:.

Represents a Struts action. Such an action typically is associated with a form bean. This action model element extends a transition, but the actual logic contained by the action envelops all action states called, until either a final state or JSP page is reached.
The action name corresponding to this action, as found in the struts deployment descriptor. The action name maps the action to a form bean.
Tthe action path corresponding to this action, as found in the struts deployment descriptor. The action path specifies the URL to enter in order to call the action.
The action input corresponding to this action, as found in the struts deployment descriptor. The action input maps the action to the page on which it originated.

The action roles corresponding to this action, as found in the struts deployment descriptor. The action roles specifiy the roles in which the user must be in order to be authorized to call the action. One of the roles must be satisfied.
Specifies whether or not this action is represented by the posting of a form.
Specifies whether or not this action is represented by clicking on a hyperlink.
A good Java class name for this action. The name is constructed from the source page and the name of the trigger.
Returns the class name of the form bean associated to this action.
The name of the form bean associated to this action. The name is returned as it should appear in the Struts deployment descriptor.
The Javascript function name of the validation method that will validate the action parameters.
True if it should be possible to reset the form represented by this action. False otherwise.
True if this action starts the use-case. False otherwise.
The full path for this action. The full path also contains the package name rendered as directories.
Returns the full path for the form bean associated to this action.
The root of the action path, this is the same as the path for the use-case context for this action, that is, the use-case holding the activity graph in which this action is contained.
True if this action requires validation, false otherwise. An action requires validation if it represented by a form and one or more fields require validation.
The fully qualified name of the form bean associated to this action.
The documentation for this action as a String that can be used as a resource message (with the backslashes at the end of the line).
A key suited as a resource message key for the documentation for this action.
The name of a file that can be used as a JSP file name in case you want to have each action rendered onto a different tile.
True if this action contains a parameter of type Date. The generated pages will contain special javascript code to handle them (popup window etc...).
True if this action contains a parameter which requires a calendar popup.
True if a table link name has been specified and it properly targets a table page-variable from the input page.
The key to lookup the online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model.
The online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model. The format is HTML without any style.
The scope in which the form bean will be placed (could be page, request, session or application).
The package for the form bean.
The fully qualified name for the action class.
The name of the CSS id in which this action will be contained.
Defines whether or not when this action's forward is executed, an HTTP redirect should occur. Default value is based on the value of the 'defaultActionRedirect' namespace.
The scope to place the current "form" variable within when this action is executing.
Indicates if the form scope is of type "session".
Indicates if the from scope is of type "request".
Indicates if the form scope is of type "none".
The name of the table link specified for this action.
The name of the column targetted by this action.
Specifies whether or not this action is represented by clicking on an image.
If this action is an imageLink this property represents the path to the corresponding image.
The resource message key used to look to location of the image for this action.
Denotes this action works on all rows of the table from the table link relation.
Denotes this action works on a single row of the table from the table link relation.
True is this action is supposed to be rendered as enctype="multipart/form-data" on the page form.
Gets all those parameters that should be reset after action execution.
The jsp on which this action can be triggered.
The set of pages that are a possible target of the triggering of this action.
Returns all exception handlers for this action.
This table action's parameters not mapped to any table column. Only makes sense when this is a table form action.
Returns all parameters transported in this action.
The controller operations to which this action defers, the order is preserved.
Returns all action forwards for this action. Each action forward either calls a JSP page or another use-case (which is essentially an action).
All action parameters that represent 'hidden' widgets.
Returns the controller that will handle the execution of this action. This controller is set as the context of the activity graph (and therefore also of the use-case).
Returns all action states visited by this action.
If the action is a table link then this property represents the table to which is being linked.
Returns all the transitions coming out of decision points. These transitions should all carry guards.
All the transitions that make up this action, this directly maps onto the forwards.
Returns all form fields for this action. Form fields are those parameters that can be altered by the user at runtime.
Returns the trigger that calls this action. Typically this is a button or an hyperlink.

Those parameters that are directly entering a final state and have been submitted into the request, they will be able to survive a trip to the next use-case. All returned elements are of type StrutsParameter.
A Struts JSP represents a page in the web application. A page possibly contains several forms and triggers (either buttons or hyperlinks) that call actions.
The full path to this JSP page. the returned String does not have a suffix such as '.jsp'.
A resource message key suited for the page's title.
A default resource message value suited for the page's title.
The default resource message key.
A resource message key suited for the page's documentation.
A resource message value suited for the page's documentation.
True if at least one client/server parameter requires validation.
True if any of the actions have a parameter of type Date.
True if this JSP contains a date field which requires a calendar popup.
The key to lookup the online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model.
The online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model. The format is HTML without any style.
A displayable version of this page's name.
The name of the file containing specific styles for this page only.
The full path to this JSP's online help action. The returned String does not have a suffix such as '.do'.
The full path to this JSP's online help page. The returned String does not have a suffix such as '.jsp'.
The collection of outgoing forwards that are not actions.
Returns all actions that possibly result in returning this page.
Returns all those variables that will be present as variables in the target page. These are the trigger parameters on the incoming transitions.
A Struts exception handler intercepts action exceptions and delegates them into a page that will handle it, by for example simply displaying it.
The key to use with this handler's message resource bundle that will retrieve the error message template for this exception.
Fully qualified Java class name of the exception type to register with this handler.
The module-relative URI to the resource that will complete the request/response if this exception occurs.
A final state represents the end of a use-case. In a Struts application this means a transition into the next use-case.

A final state maps onto a use-case. The full path to this use-case is returned here. In case no name for this final state was specified the use-case with the application's first use-case path will be returned.
A Struts parameter is an object communicated between the client and the server. Typically form beans encapsulate such parameters.
The default message key for this parameter.
The default message value for this parameter.
True if this parameter is either an array type or java.util.Collection type.
The backing list name for this parameter. This is useful if you want to be able to select the parameter value from a list.
True if the value of this parameter must be reset between requests (Struts requires this for specific types), false otherwise.
The null value for the type of this parameter. For decimals this would be zero, for booleans this would be 'false', etc...
The widget type for this parameter, this value is the tagname for the Struts HTML taglib. This method is useful only when rendering forms.

The reset value for this parameter. The reset value is the non-null value to which this parameter is set by default between requests, you can use this method to be able to generate an application that will deploy and run with default data.
True if this parameter cannot be changed by the user, false otherwise.
The reset value for this parameter's value list. Only makes sense if this parameter is selectable.
A collection of all the validator types for this parameter. Use this value in conjunction with the Struts validator plugin.
The message key for this parameter, equivalent to getMessageKey().
The validator arguments.
The validator's 'validwhen' value, this is useful when the validation of a parameter depends on the validation of others. See the Struts validator plugin documentation for more information.

If this parameter is a choice between radio buttons, then you may use this method to retrieve the message keys for the resource bundle. The message keys hold the value to be displayed for the possible options.

The maximum number of rows to be displayed in the table at the same time. This is also known as the page size. A value of zero or less will display all data in the same table (therefore also on the same page).
True if it is possible to export the table data to XML, CSV, PDF or Excel format.
True if it is possible to sort the columns of the table.
Tthe available types of export in a single String instance.
True if this parameter requires some kind of validation. This means the collection of validator types is not empty.
True if the type of this parameter represents a date. This is equivalent to parameter.type.isDateType().
If this parameter represents a date this method will return the format in which it must be represented. In case this format has not been specified by the any tagged value a default one will be taken.
True if the date format is to be strictly respected. Otherwise the dateformatter used for the representation of this date is to be set to lenient.
True if this parameter is a date and it requires a calendar popup.
The package name of the decorator to use for the table.
The class name of the decorator to use for the table.
The full path to the decorator class.
The values for the options. Only makes sense when the widget type is radiobutton. The property value may directly be specified usiing the tagged value.
In case this parameter represents an option set using radiobuttons, this attribute is a positive integer and zero otherwise.
The key to lookup the documentation for this parameter.
The documentation for this parameter, formatted to be inserted into a resource bundle.
The key to lookup the online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model.
The online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model. The format is HTML without any style.
Whether or not this parameter is selectable. In case this would be true this parameter always has a backing list, a value list and a list containing the labels.
The name of the list holding the values for this parameter. Only makes sense when the parameter is selectable.
The name of the list holding the labels for this parameter. Only makes sense when the parameter is selectable.

If this parameter is a collection type, this property will represent the fully qualified name of a class suitable for implementation. If the type is neither Collection, List, nor Set the type itself is assumed.
The name of the array to be used for the multibox, this only makes sense when this parameter is actually a multibox.
Whether or not this parameter should be reset between requests. This is different than resetRequired in that this is user specified.
The name of the operation that resets this parameter to its original value.
True if this parameter represents a password field.
The complete table decorator classname.
True if this table has form actions that share the column widgets. It is not allowed to have different actions use different widgets on the same column.

True if this parameter represents a table column into which an hyperlink must be rendered. This property only makes sense when it has been called on parameters representing an actual table column. Note that the getTableColumns() operation also returns String instances.
Indicates if a table can be sorted by this parameter.
The time format for this parameter (if this parameter stores time).
Indicates if this parameter's type represents a time.

This property is used in model validation. It denotes whether all actions targetting this table page-variable take the same parameter (same name and type). Only makes sense when this parameter is actually a table page-variable.
The number of rows for this field, null if default browser value is desired.
The number of columns for this field, null if default browser value is desired.
True if this parameter has a name that can properly be handled by Jakarta commons (this lib is used by Struts but contains a bug)
Those actions that are working on this table and are to be represented as hyperlinks. It only makes sense to call this property on parameters that represent a table page-variable.
Represents the jsp page in which this parameter will be used: either as a page variable, either as an action parameter (form or hyperlink).
The column which is chosen to be submitted by the action targetting the entire table. Only makes sense when there are actually global table actions present for this table parameter.
If this is a controller operation argument these form fields will represent the form fields for all actions deferring to the controller operation.
Returns those actions that allow table rows to be checked and submitted. Only makes sense when this parameter represents a table page-variable.

The actions used when submitting forms for this table. Table actions that are hyperlinks are not included. It only makes sense to call this property on parameters that represent a table page-variable.
Returns the arguments for this parameter's validators.
Returns the resource bundle key for this table's column, only returns a value when this parameter is a table.
Returns the resource bundle value for this table's column, only returns a value when this parameter is a table.
Those actions that are targetting this table's columns, only makes sense when this parameter represents a table page-variable.
A Struts use-case represents a set of related client/server requests and communication.
The title message key for this use-case.
The title message value for this use-case.
This use-case's action path.
The root of the action path.

Returns the action roles corresponding to this use-case's action, as found in the struts deployment descriptor. The action roles specifiy the roles in which the user must be in order to be authorized to call the action. One of the roles must be satisfied.
True if at least one client/server parameter found in the collection of existing use-cases requires validation.
True if some client/server parameters require validation for this use-case.
The key to lookup the online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model.
The online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model. The format is HTML without any style.
True if this use-case is where the application starts.

The root node of the application usecase hierarchy. Only makes sense when this usecase is an application usecase. Each usecase is only listed once in it's subtree, meaning when cycles ar edetected in the applicaion usecase graph the usecase will not be added when it already exists as an ancestor.

The root of the hierarchy of application usecases where this usecase is at the top. It is possible not all usecases are included in the descendants, they can be found in the collection of ancestor nodes.
The name of the file containing specific styles for this use-case only.
A map with keys sorted alphabetically, normalized across all different use-cases and pages etc..
The full path to this use-case's online help page. The returned String does not have a suffix such as '.jsp'.
The full path to this use-case's online help action. The returned String does not have a suffix such as '.do'.
The key under which to store the forms contained in this use-case.
The variables for all pages in this use-case. A parameter qualifies to be a variable when it explicitly and directly receives it via an action.
This method returns all pages in the application. A page is an action state with the FrontEndView stereotype.
Returns the form fields used in this use-case, in fact these are all the parameters used in client/server communication for this use-case.
This method returns all pages in the use-case. A page is an action state with the FrontEndView stereotype.
A Struts forward is any transition between states. Some of these forwards may end up as actual forwards in the Struts deployment descriptor.
The name for this forward. This name is always lowercase and words are separated using dots, not unlike the convention for Java package names.
Returns the path targetted by this forward.
If this forward is guarded (such as with decision points) this method return the name of that guard.
True if this action directly targets a JSP page, false otherwise.
The resource bundle key of the name for the target element. This method returns the key for the use-case or jsp page. If targetting anything else this method returns null.
Whether or not this forward (transition) is coming out of a page.
A map of key=value pairs, one for each success message.
A map of key=value pairs, one for each warning message.
Returns the activity graph which holds this action if the graph is contained in a FrontEndUseCase.
Encapsulates a pseudostate and provides specific Struts services. This pseudostate can be a decision point, junction or initial state.
The method name that delegates transitions from this state.
A plain action state represents an operation on the server called by an action. Optionally an action state may defer operations to the controller.
Represents the activity graph describing the details of a Struts use-case.
Returns the first action encountered in this activity graph. This is the one and only transition coming out of the initial state.
A Struts trigger is represented by clicking a hyperlink or posting an action form.
The message key to use as a tooltip when the user is not allowed to use this trigger.
The message title key to use as a tooltip for this trigger.
The message reset title key to use as a tooltip for this trigger's reset feature.
Returns the message key to use as a tooltip when the user is not allowed to use reset the form behind this trigger.
The message reset key for this trigger.
The resource message value for this trigger, this would be the button label or hyperlink name.
The default resource message value for this trigger's tooltip.
The tooltip value for this trigger's reset feature.
The message value to use as a tooltip when the user is not allowed to use reset the form behind this trigger.
The message value to use as a tooltip when the user is not allowed to use this trigger.
True if this trigger is modeled on an action transition. That means, the transition is coming out of an action state with the FrontEndView stereotype. False otherwise.
The message key to use for reset button labels.
The message value to use for reset button labels.
If isActionTrigger() returns true them this association points to the action to which the trigger has been associated.
A controller is assigned as the context of a use-case. All manual implementation is done in the controller as Struts actions may result in derferring method calls to this controller.
The full path to this controller (that is the full file system path made up from the package and name).
The session objects that this controller has access to.
Returns all the arguments found in this controller's operations. Please note that return types are excluded from this collection.

ownedRule.name: name must uniquely match usecase

ownedComment.body: The name of this final state must not be null and exactly match the name of a use-case. Alternatively it is possible to reference a use-case using an hyperlink (some UML tools support this). In both cases that use-case MUST carry the FrontEndUseCase stereotype. Finally you may also specify an actual hyperlink to an external resource, either in the final state's name, or as a webpage link as supported by some UML tools.

specification.body: context StrutsFinalState inv: fullPath->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: controller must have a name

ownedComment.body: Each controller must have a name, it cannot be empty.

specification.body: context StrutsController inv: name->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: each action trigger must have a name

ownedComment.body: Every trigger modeled on a transition going out of a FrontEndView action state must have a name. These triggers are known as action-triggers.

specification.body: context StrutsTrigger inv: transition.exitingPage implies name->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: session object needs a name

ownedComment.body: Each session object needs a good name, it will be used to look up the actual instance in the session scope.

specification.body: context StrutsSessionObject inv: name->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: no more than one usecase per package

ownedComment.body: In order to avoid possible naming collisions at most one FrontEndUseCase per package is allowed. It is recommended to refactor your model.

specification.body: context StrutsPackage inv: strutsUseCases->size() < 2

ownedRule.name: no more than one controller per package

ownedComment.body: In order to avoid possible naming collisions at most one controller per package is allowed. It is recommended to refactor your model.

specification.body: context StrutsPackage inv: strutsControllers->size() < 2

ownedRule.name: each action must carry a trigger

ownedComment.body: Each action transition coming out of a page must have a trigger (the name could be sufficient), it is recommended to add a trigger of type 'signal'.

specification.body: context StrutsAction inv: exitingPage implies triggerPresent

ownedRule.name: graph must have an action modeled on it's initial state

ownedComment.body: Each activity graph must have an action transition exiting the initial state, this is the minimum required.

specification.body: context StrutsActivityGraph inv: firstAction->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: each controller operation argument must be used by deferring actions

ownedComment.body: All actions deferring to controller operations must have a parameter or page-variable with the same name for all arguments of those operations. Failing to do so will lead to uncompilable code.

specification.body: context StrutsParameter inv: controllerOperationArgument implies formFields->size() = controllerOperation.deferringActions->size()

ownedRule.name: must target page or final state

ownedComment.body: When you model an action-exception you must either target a FrontEndView action state or a final state.

specification.body: context StrutsExceptionHandler inv: enteringPage = false implies enteringFinalState

ownedRule.name: non-empty controller operation names

ownedComment.body: Each operation name on a controller must be non-empty.

specification.body: context StrutsControllerOperation inv: name->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: unique operation names

ownedComment.body: A controller cannot have different operations with the same name, even if they have a different signature.

specification.body: context StrutsController inv: operations->isUnique(name)

ownedRule.name: decision forwards need a controller operation with a non-void return type

ownedComment.body: If a transition is going into a decision point you will need to defer to an operation with a non-void return type. You will need to model this on the transition's trigger.

specification.body: context StrutsForward inv: enteringDecisionPoint implies (decisionTrigger->notEmpty() and operationCall->notEmpty() and operationCall.returnTypePresent)

ownedRule.name: decision outcome needs a guard

ownedComment.body: When a transition exits a decision point it needs a guard with a non-empty name.

specification.body: context StrutsForward inv: exitingDecisionPoint implies guardName->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: validate decision points

ownedComment.body: Transitions carrying a controller call in their triggers need to target a decision point, this is a diamond shaped figure with 2 or more outgoing transitions.

specification.body: context StrutsForward inv: operationCall->notEmpty() and target.oclIsKindOf(org::andromda::metafacades::uml::PseudostateFacade) and (target.choice or target.junction) implies enteringDecisionPoint

ownedRule.name: operation calls must target a decision point

ownedComment.body: If you defer to an operation call on a transition, than that transition must target a decision point.

specification.body: context StrutsForward inv: operationCall->notEmpty() implies (target.oclIsKindOf(org::andromda::metafacades::uml::PseudostateFacade) and target.decisionPoint)

ownedRule.name: session object needs public attributes

ownedComment.body: All attributes on a session object must have a public visibility.

specification.body: context StrutsSessionObject inv : attributes -> forAll(visibility = 'public')

ownedRule.name: table links must target an existing table page-variable

ownedComment.body: When specifying a table link for this action you will need to target a table page-variable from the input page, the specified table does not exist in that page.

specification.body: context StrutsAction inv: tableLinkName->notEmpty() implies tableLink

ownedRule.name: table hyperlinks cannot share columns

ownedComment.body: When different hyperlink actions are targetting this table it is not allowed let them have parameters with the same name. Each hyperlink should target a different table column.

specification.body: context StrutsParameter inv: table implies not tableHyperlinkActionSharingColumns

ownedRule.name: table form actions need parameters sharing widgets

ownedComment.body: Different form actions targetting this table must not specify different widgets for shared parameters. Per parameter only a single widget can be used and you will need to repeat this for each form action using that parameter.

specification.body: context StrutsParameter inv: table implies tableFormActionSharingWidgets

ownedRule.name: table event parameters must match a table column

ownedComment.body: Each table event parameter must have a name matching a column in the target table.

specification.body: context StrutsParameter inv: action.tableLink implies action.tableLinkParameter.tableColumnNames->includes(self = name)

ownedRule.name: hyperlink table actions need to indicate the column

ownedComment.body: This hyperlink table event is not specifying the target column name on the table link, you will need to do this in order to determine in which column to render the hyperlink.

specification.body: context StrutsAction inv: (hyperlink and tableLink) implies tableLinkColumnName->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: all tablelink event parameters must have known column names

specification.body: context StrutsAction inv: (hyperlink and tableLink) implies actionParameters->forAll()

ownedRule.name: controller/service operations need matching parameter types and names

ownedComment.body: If a controller operation delegates to a service operation it is required for them to have the same number of parameters and to have the parameter names and types matching so it is straightforward to pass these on.

specification.body: context StrutsControllerOperation inv: backEndServiceOperation->notEmpty() implies backEndServiceOperationMatchingParameters

ownedRule.name: use-cases that loop need at least one page

ownedComment.body: This use-case has a final state targetting the same use-case, while at the same time no pages have been modeled. This will lead to an infinite loop at runtime since the same event will keep invoking itself.

specification.body: context StrutsUseCase inv: cyclic implies pages->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: required fields may not be hidden

ownedComment.body: Required fields may not be hidden, unless they are auto-generated identifiers.

specification.body: context StrutsManageableEntityAttribute inv: (required and not (identifier and owner.dynamicIdentifiersPresent)) implies not hidden

ownedRule.name: widget type cannot be arbitrary

ownedComment.body: Only text, textarea and hidden widgets are supported, please select another one or let the cartridge decide by not specifying anything.

specification.body: context StrutsManageableEntityAttribute inv: widgetType->notEmpty() implies (widgetType = 'text' or widgetType = 'textarea' or widgetType = 'hidden')

ownedRule.name: front end graph must have a controller context

ownedComment.body: An activity graph must have a controller class context to which (optionally) operations can be deferred. Make sure this graph's use-case has the FrontEndUseCase stereotype.

specification.body: context FrontEndActivityGraph inv: controller->notEmpty()

ownedRule.name: table actions must all have one parameter

ownedComment.body: All actions targetting this table and operating on all visible rows at the same time can only have a single parameter, this parameter denotes the value that will be sent when the row has been selected.

specification.body: context StrutsParameter inv: tableGlobalActions->notEmpty() implies tableGlobalActions->forAll(actionParameters->size() = 1)

ownedRule.name: all global table action must have the same parameter

ownedComment.body: All actions targetting this table and operating on the entire rowset must have the same event parameter declaration, this means both name and type must match for all parameters in these actions.

specification.body: context StrutsParameter inv: tableGlobalActions->notEmpty() implies allGlobalTableActionsHaveSameParameter

ownedRule.name: SAFE NAME - TO BE REMOVED LATER

ownedComment.body: The names you give to fields cannot start with a lowercase character directly followed by a character in uppercase. This is due to a bug in the Jakarta commons library which is used by Struts. The behavior of that library is inconsistent with the reflection API provided by the JDK. Please rename this field or you'll get exceptions when running your web application.

specification.body: context StrutsAttribute inv: safeNamePresent

ownedRule.name: controller name should not resemble the usecase name

ownedComment.body: The name of this front-end controller resembles the name of the use-case it is associated with. You'll have to rename it in order to avoid naming collisions (generated files will overwrite eachother).

specification.body: context StrutsController inv: name <> useCase.activityGraph.firstAction.actionClassName

ownedComment.body: The key to which the instance of this object will be mapped in the session.
The full path to the session object class file (comparable to the package name).

The name of the interface used for forms that correspond to the calling of this operation (we need to pass the form to the controller, but many forms/actions my be deferring to this operation, this way we can aggregate them).

The package of the interface used for forms that correspond to the calling of this operation (we need to pass the form to the controller, but many forms/actions my be deferring to this operation, this way we can aggregate them).
The package of the interface converted to a file-system compatible format.
The fully qualified name of the interface.
If this is true then the backEndServiceOperation property is not null, meaning this operation is calling a specific backend operation.
The controller for this operation. This is the owner in case this actually is a controller operation, null otherwise.
The actions leading directly into this action state.
The implementation to use in a controller template in order to get an instance of this service.
The key to lookup the online help documentation.
The online help documentation. The format is HTML without any style.
The full path to this entity's online help action. The returned String does not have a suffix such as '.do'.
The full path to this entitiy's online help page. The returned String does not have a suffix such as '.jsp'.
True if it is possible to export the table data to XML, CSV, PDF or Excel format.
Tthe available types of export in a single String instance.

The maximum number of rows to be displayed in the table at the same time. This is also known as the page size. A value of zero or less will display all data in the same table (therefore also on the same page).
True if it is possible to sort the columns of the table.
True is this action is supposed to be rendered as enctype="multipart/form-data" on the page form.
The String format to use when referring to this date, only makes sense when the type is a date type.
True if this attribute is of a type that cannot easily be represented as a textual string and would be an ideal candidate for HTTP's support for file-upload.
Whether or not this attribute should be hidden from the view
The widget to use when rendering this attribute
True if this field is a date type and the date format is not be interpreted strictly.
The number of rows for this field, null if default browser value is desired.
The number of columns for this field, null if default browser value is desired.
True if this parameter has a name that can properly be handled by Jakarta commons (this lib is used by Struts but contains a bug)
The key to lookup the online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model.
The online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model. The format is HTML without any style.
True if this parameter has a name that can properly be handled by Jakarta commons (this lib is used by Struts but contains a bug)
The key to lookup the online help documentation. This documentation is gathered from the documentation entered by the user, as well as analyzing the model.
